title: For Sale/Trade:  Antique Colt for sale
postcontent:
Rare/Transitional 1906 Colt Police Positive

This is the Colt police positive in the 38 colt (38 S&W/38 short) caliber. It has the uncommon barrel length of 6 inches, and the original grips. This is called a transitional gun because the barrel is stamped colt police positive, but the sideplate is stamped "Colt's new police"  which was only done for the first couple years of production. The serial number on this revolver places it as one manufactured in early-mid 1906, the second year of production.

 I have had this fire arm looked at by a professional and they said that it is in good, shooting order.  I have never fired it, but you can if you want to. 

This revolver is in pristine condition with virtually flawless, original grips.  It has very mild holster wear, but has obviously withstood the test of time.  It comes with a box of antique 38 colt police positive ammunition and a box of 38 S&W ammunition. 

**This is not one of the cheapo 32 calibers or 4 inch barrel 38's that are a dime a dozen.**

Brands ranging from Blackhawk, VooDoo Tactical, 5.11 Tactical, Condor and more. Here's a more detailed breakdown of many of the items available: Note: The black vest pictured is the last one on-hand. 

Here are specs on only the vest (does not include molle pouches): 
•Manufacturer/Model:  Condor Outdoors / Modular LBV, tactical black
•Material: Mold/Mildew/UV resistant Cordura ballistic nylon

•Mag pouches run flush along external molle webbing for seamless fit when not in use

I've used mine as simply a LBV with a couple 4" molle straps and a Blackhawk rigger's belt doing tree-trimming and had tools in every position (occasionally would take the bladder out and throw in 50' of climbing rope), then gone the next weekend to teach a 3-day course at the TDI institute and worn it over a full upper body MAR CIRAS carrier with A46100 level 4 ballistic plates.

Steve

I was never quite happy with the accuracy of it so I had some work done to it by Oregon Timberwolf.  I had the trigger adjusted to 2.5 lbs, machined the rear of the receiver flat, and then glass bedded.  It was also cerakoted while at the shop. title: For Sale:  Cobra Amp Cell-S combo iron set
postcontent:
I bought these clubs last winter from Dicks for around $500. They are in great shape, with a little bit of normal wear on the club faces due to ball striking, as I only played one season with them and always take good care of my clubs. The set consists of:  4H & 5H, 6-PW, SW; all with regular flex shafts and head covers for both hybrids.

These are some of the longest irons I have ever hit. The only problems were the regular flex shafts and natural offset of the irons which, combined, greatly opened up my shot dispersion and promoted a little too much draw tendency for my swing. The salesperson mistakenly got me regular flex instead of the stiff I normally swing, and being right in the middle of the offseason, I didn't get a chance to swing the clubs and realize the mistake until it was too late to return them. That said, these would be a great set for a beginner or someone with a slower swing speed as they are very forgiving and incredibly easy to get airborne. Also, the 4 and 5 hybrids are a lot easier to hit than their traditional 4 and 5 iron counterparts.
